Introduction

Lepidopteras play valuable roles in the terrestrial ecosystems of the word. They are an order of insects cosnsisting of 160,000 species of butterflies and moths. They have both forewings and hindwings, each playing roles in functions such as flying and attracting mates. Even when their hindwing is cut off, reducing the surface area of their wing by one half, they are able to keep flying. However, with this loss of wing, the ability for linear flight and acceleration is severely weakened (Jantzen and Eisner 2008). Hindwings are essential in survival, enabling normal flight function and allowing lepidopterans to evade and defend against predators such as bats and birds. The size variation in the forewings and hindwings has allowed the lepidoptera to obtain high levels of flight and speed as well as directional inconsistnacy, which have evolved to pritotize these functions. The purpose of this study is to determine if the rates of wing-shape evolution between the hindwing and forweing are similar and if they have undergone significant shifts among lineages. Furthermore, we wanted to discover if these hindwing and forewing shapes were correlated with each other. The wings will be evaluated and compared through the phylogenetic analysis of over 200 species of Lepidoptera in a certain taxa.

Methods

Image Acquisition

Images analyzed in this project were acquired by downloading the R package, rgif, which permits access to the Global Biodiversity Information Facilitys (GBIF) application programming interface. Records from GBIF were now accessible for all Lepidoptera analyzed below.

Digitization

Right-wing shapes across ~200 species of Lepidoptera were examined utilizing the image analysis program FIJI. After opening each image, the following sequence was followed depending on scale bar, wing damage, and hindwing exposure. If a scale bar was present, the scale was set in mm. If the right-wing pair was damaged, the image was flipped horizontally. The wings were then traced utilizing the polygon selection tool. A script was created, and the selected points (x and y coordinates) were exported in a .txt file for further analysis.

Shape & Comparative Analysis

Outline-based shape analysis, utilizing Elliptical Fourier Analysis (EFA) and Principal Components Analysis (PCA), were performed to compare shape change between species. PCA plot output for both forewing and hindwing can be referenced below (Figures 1 & 2). Evolutionary rates of the PC scores were observed across the Lepidoptera tree (Kawahara et al. 2019) and species information was added (Figure 3).

Figure 1: Biplot visualization of PCA 1 and 2 in the forewings

Figure 2: Biplot visualization of PCA 1 and 2 in the hindwings

Figure 3: Phylogenetic tree based on Kawahara et al. (2019) study on Lepidoptera. The same tree is modified to include only species observed in PC analysis and merged with PC data to visualize evolutionary rate shifts

Evolutionary Rates & Shifts

The non-censored test (OMeara et al. 2006) was utilized to estimate the rates of morphological evolution over a phylogenetic tree. Phylogenetic ridge regression (Kratsch and McHardy 2014) was then utilized to determine whether the evolutionary shift was to a slower or faster rate. The regressions are based on the phenotype values at each node vs.time between nodes and along the path. The value of the slope parameter of these regressions is the rate.

Shape Evolution Correlation

Phylogenetic independent contrasts (PIC) analysis was performed to investigate the correlation in hind and forewing shape evolution. R-squared values were then found by creating a linear model.

Results

Evolutionary Rates: Hindwing vs.Forewing

Evolution Rate Estimate of PC1 in Forewing
## [1] 0.006535527
Evolution Rate Estimate of PC2 in Forewing
## [1] 0.002411568
Evolution Rate Estimate of PC1 in Hindwing
## [1] 0.01014157
Evolution Rate Estimate of PC2 in Hindwing
## [1] 0.01870921

The evolutionary rates of the forewing and hindwing are quite different. The hindwing seems to evolve at a rate almost twice as fast as the forewing. The PC1 rates show the forewing to be undergoing evolutionary shifts at a rate of 0.006535527 versus the rate of 0.01014157 in the hindwing. This suggests the hindwing changes are occuring much more frequently in size and shape to promote advantageous factors in the Lepodoptra.The PC2 as well shows a large increase in evolutionary rates in the hindwing.

Figures 4-7 depict the evolutionary shift rate in hindwings and forewings. The p-value of PC1 and PC2 are .001, telling us the difference in evolutionary rate between the labeled phyla and the rest of the tree is significant. The PC1 data for both forewing and hindwing show there has been an exceptional downward rate shift in a certain crown group on the phylogenetic tree. The blue triangle pointed down represents that the Macroheterocera: Noctuoidea group has undergone a low evolutionary shift in terms of aspect ratio (PC1) of the hindwing, and wing lobe deveopment (PC2) of the forewing. The crown-Obtectomera: Papilionoidea has undergone a low evolutionary shift as well for both lobe development (hindwing PC2), and aspect ratio (forewing PC2). Lowered rates of evolution can indicate conservation of existing traits, selecting against mutations that would otherwise change the phenotype and cause evolution.

Since there is also no significant change in the R-squared values from that in Figure 8, the linear model with only forewing PC1 would be the best and most straightforward predictor for hindwing PC1.

In a multivariate context, the relationships of forewing PC1 and PC2 with hindwing PC2 do not change. There also is no significant interaction. As a summary, there is a very strong and significant negative relationship between hindwing PC1 and forewing PC1. There is also a relatively significant positive relationship between hindwing PC2 and forewing PC1. The shape of the hingwing is therefore correlated with the shape of the forewing to a certain extent.

Discussion

The Lepidoptera species use a set of wings, a forewing and hindwing for a plethora of survival functions such as movement, reproduction, and eating as well. These pairs of wings provide flight to all of these functions, and without them the species would not be able to transport themselves where necessary to survive. Like many species, their parts, such as these forewings and hindwings have evolved (Kawahara et al. 2019). The Papilionoidea group showed a lack of variation in wing size, shown in the results of the PC2. This indicates that there is a conservation of wing size among this group. PC1 and PC2 were transformed into phylogenetic information, and it was found that PC2 did not carry significance, with an R-squared value of 0.4442. It was also found that PC1 did carry significance with an R-squared value of 0.4121. There are many different reasons for evolutionary changes in wing shapes, such as varying competition levels in the ecology, or constraints due to the environment. Groups of species that live among many different species, especially predators, may experience low aspect ratio, whereas groups who are migrating frequently for varying reasons may have high aspect ratio (Kawahara et al. 2019).
